{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539724"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:45:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:45:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16697"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16697","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16697"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.05,0.71,0.01,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9388"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66399"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9388","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9388"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16697"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51850"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1803"},{"type":"tags","id":"2780"},{"type":"tags","id":"8054"},{"type":"tags","id":"8798"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22206"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39872"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66399","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66399"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 78-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of a watery, red right eye. She reports constantly feeling something in her right eye. She has noticed that her right lower eyelid looks rolled or turned differently. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The right lower eyelid margin is turned inward, with no nodules or rashes noted.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trichiasis","Dacryocystitis","Entropion","Basal cell carcinoma","Ectropion"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of involutional \u003Cstrong\u003Eentropion\u003C/strong\u003E, which is an inward turning of the eyelid margin commonly seen in elderly patients. The key features are epiphora (excessive tearing), red eye, ocular irritation, dry eye syndrome and potential corneal damage from the inward-turning eyelashes. The condition typically results from age-related weakening of the lid retractors and orbicularis muscle overriding, with loss of orbital fat content from age.  It may occur on the upper or lowers lids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther types of entropions are cicatricial entropion (from chronic inflammation causing scarring), spastic entropion and congenital entropion which are not likely accounting for this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEctropion\u003C/strong\u003E is an outward turning of the eyelid margin. While it can also cause tearing and irritation, the eyelid turns outward rather than inward as seen in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrichiasis\u003C/strong\u003E refers to misdirected eyelashes that grow toward and touch the cornea. While this can cause irritation and tearing, it occurs without lid margin malposition and would show visible lashes touching the cornea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBasal cell carcinoma\u003C/strong\u003E of the lower eyelid typically presents as a pearly nodule with rolled edges, telangiectasia, and possible ulceration. While it can affect eyelid position and has typical rolled edges over the lesion, the absence of any visible lesions makes this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDacryocystitis\u003C/strong\u003E is infection of the lacrimal sac, typically presenting with pain and swelling near the medial canthus. While it can cause tearing, it would not cause the anatomical lid changes seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EManagement of entropion depends on severity. Temporary relief can be achieved with lubricating drops and lid taping. In some cases, botolinum toxin injections can be done. However, definitive treatment usually requires surgical correction to address the underlying anatomical problem.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Entropion is an inward turning of the eyelid margin, most commonly affecting the lower lid in elderly patients.","Key symptoms of entropion include epiphora (excessive tearing), ocular irritation, and corneal abrasion from inward-turning lashes.","Conservative management with lubricating drops and taping can provide temporary relief, while definitive treatment is surgical correction."],"references":["Hakim F et al. Entropion and ectropion.  Disease-a-Month Journal. 2020: 66(10).  Available at: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/S0011502920301012","Weber A et al. Entropion.  American Academy of Ophthalmology EyeWiki. 2024. Available at: https://eyewiki.org/Entropion"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51850"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16697"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51850"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T23:30:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-12T19:25:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9388"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66399"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/8"},"attributes":{"emoji":"